SSD-based graph processing systems have emerged as a cost-effective solution for handling the ever-growing, large-scale graphs that exceed the memory capacity of a single machine. However, the mismatch between the large SSD access granularity (e.g., 4KB) and the small size of the graph vertex data leads to significant read amplification and low I/O efficiency. Despite existing works proposing techniques like dynamic active data gathering or reordering-based graph preprocessing to tackle this challenge, they inevitably cause problems such as expensive on-line computation overheads, inefficient graph traversal, and I/O imbalance, thus degrading the performance of graph processing. In this paper, we propose Graphago, an activity-aware graph preprocessing technique for SSD-based graph processing systems. The main idea of Graphago is the combined use of three key designs that synergistically optimize the graph storage and organization based on the active extent of graph data, thereby achieving both high I/O efficiency and satisfactory processing performance: 1) a dual-centrality activity prediction model that efficiently predicts the active extent of each vertex by considering both its local connectivity and global importance, 2) an activity-neighborhood graph ordering technique that reorganizes the graph based on vertex activity and neighbor relationships to minimize read amplification without sacrificing graph traversal efficiency, and 3) an active-data-balanced graph partitioning scheme that evenly distributes high-activity vertices/edges across all graph partitions to address I/O imbalance. Our evaluation results show that Graphago outperforms state-of-the-art SSD-based graph processing systems by up to 4.8×, with higher I/O efficiency and reasonable preprocessing overheads.